# An Internet Connected (Railway Signal) Lamp

While working at eBay, we were always encouraged to "be the customer". Essentially that meant, buy and sell stuff on eBay.

eBay was my first job after graduating from University, and I still lived at home. I didn't really _need_ anything, but I had to buy _something_. So what do I buy? An old railway signal.

## The Signal Head
The signal head itself is a fairly standard 2 aspect signal, with side lights. I don't know the correct term for these, but I've always known them as Pig's Ears. They're used for when the driver has drawn right up to the signal, and can't see the main lens. 

It has a Green Aspect:
![Green Aspect](data:image/png;base64,)

And it has a Red Aspect:
![Red aspect](data:image/png;base64,)

The Signal Identification Plate that came with it reads `FC9`. It's not a standard BR plate, but has black letters on a white background, which leads me to believe that it's ex-London Underground, and I think FC identifies it as being a signal from the Barking area, more specifically Plaistow in the late 1950s, and early 1960s [according to Railway Codes](http://www.railwaycodes.org.uk/signal/signal_boxesX.shtm)... Assuming, of course, that the plate is the right one for the signal, and both are genuine! 

So that now means I am the proud owner of a solid lump of cast iron and glass. So that leads me to my next question...

## How can I introduce software to this signal?
> **Answer**: By connecting it to the internet!

The signal itself is relatively simple inside. When I acquired it it had 4 lamps, all on the same circuit. Meaning, all lights would either be on or off. 

Naturally, I know that with some switches, I could easily put each lamp on it's own circuit. But the back of the signal is a solid lump of metal, so no installing switches there. Nor do I want to have wires hanging out of the back. I need a wireless solution...

Wireless... Well, I have a wireless network! Let's connect it to that! I can use a Raspberry Pi to do that, with some relays. I just need to install a USB power port inside the lamp. Easy!

Plus a little bit of [Python](https://github.com/dlpb/lampserver) to write a basic web server and to interact with the relays, et voilla! An internet connected lamp!

## A bonus - HTTP 418 anyone?

There's an added bonus to this project. As any API developer would know, there are myriad HTTP status codes, including the infamous [`HTTP 418 - I'm a Teapot`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/418) code.

Now, in every day development, I never get a chance to reasonably implement `HTTP 418`, and why would I? I don't program teapots!

However, this feels like the perfect excuse to extend `HTTP 418` into I'm an `x`, where in this case `x` is a lamp! So now, if I try and `PUT`, `DELETE` etc on a resource, it will return (I feel quite correctly), the status code `418` with the message `I'm a lamp`! If nothing else, the project was worth it just to be able to do that!
